Lets look at the distribution of optimism scores. I noticed that each score is represented twice. To avoid counting both I am going to only include the posttest scores in a histogram.

hist(pols$optimism[(pols$testtime=="post")])

Lets see if political affiliation and gender are independent of each other. To do this I need to calculate the frequency that individuals appear in different political groups. Then Ill use a Chi-Square test of independence to test the hypothesis that affiliation and gender are independent. Again, I dont want to count people twice, so Ill focus on the posttest data.

tab<-table(pols$party[pols$testtime=="post"],pols$sex[pols$testtime=="post"])
tab
##              
##               female male
##   democrat        14   12
##   independent      7   10
##   republican      12   11

These are the frequencies individuals fell into the different political affiliation groups.

chisq.test(pols$party[pols$testtime=="post"],pols$sex[pols$testtime=="post"])
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  pols$party[pols$testtime == "post"] and pols$sex[pols$testtime == "post"]
## X-squared = 0.72674, df = 2, p-value = 0.6953

Political affiliation is independent of gender for optimism scores.

To see whether or not males and females have different incomes we can run an independent t-test.

t.test(pols$income[pols$sex=="male" & pols$testtime=="pre"],pols$income[pols$sex=="female" & pols$testtime=="pre"])
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  pols$income[pols$sex == "male" & pols$testtime == "pre"] and pols$income[pols$sex == "female" & pols$testtime == "pre"]
## t = -1.5714, df = 61.623, p-value = 0.1212
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -19.23627   2.30508
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  38.80751  47.27310

Males and females do differ in income. t(61.62) = -1.57, p = .12.

To create the figure, I need to include the dplyr library. Then Ill use it to summarize the politics data set and find the means and standard errors for the different conditions. Then Ill need the ggplot2 library to create a nice plot thats easy to work with. It will be the same with other graphs unless specified otherwise. I made the graph more pleasing on the eyes! This graph compares incomes of males and females.

library("dplyr")
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter
## 
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
temp<-pols[pols$testtime=="post",]%>%group_by(sex)%>%summarize(means=mean(income),
              sems=sd(income)/sqrt(length(income)))
library("ggplot2")
f<-ggplot(temp,aes(x=factor(sex),y=means))+
    geom_bar(stat="identity", color="black",fill=c("deeppink","deepskyblue2"))+
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymax=means+sems, ymin=means-sems), width=.1)
f<-f+ggtitle("Income by Sex")+
    labs(x="Sex", y="Income\n(higher=more income")+
    scale_x_discrete(breaks=c("female","male"),labels=c("Female","Male"))+
    theme(plot.title=element_text(size=15,face="bold",vjust=.5))+
    theme(axis.title.x=element_text(size=12,face="bold",vjust=-.25))+
    theme(axis.title.y=element_text(size=12,face="bold",vjust=1))+
    theme(axis.text.x=element_text(size=10,face="bold",color="black"))+
    theme(axis.text.y=element_text(size=10,face="bold",color="black"))+
    coord_cartesian(ylim=c(min(temp$means)-2*max(temp$sems),max(temp$means)+2*max(temp$sems)))+
    theme(panel.border=element_blank(), axis.line=element_line())+
    theme(panel.grid.major.x=element_blank())+
    theme(panel.grid.major.y=element_line(color="darkgrey"))+
    theme(panel.grid.minor.y=element_blank())
f

Now lets see if party affiliation and sex predict posttest optimism scores independently or in an interaction using a 2-way between-subjects ANOVA.

summary(aov(optimismscore~party*sex,data=pols[pols$testtime=="post",]))
##             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value  Pr(>F)    
## party        2  10147    5074  27.063 4.2e-09 ***
## sex          1      7       7   0.040   0.843    
## party:sex    2    455     227   1.213   0.304    
## Residuals   60  11248     187                    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
temp<-pols[pols$testtime=="post",]%>%group_by(party,sex)%>%
    summarize(means=mean(optimismscore),sems=sd(optimismscore)/sqrt(length(optimismscore)))
library("gplots")
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## 
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
col1=col2hex("deeppink")
col2=col2hex("deepskyblue2")
f<-ggplot(temp, aes(x=party, y=means, fill=sex))+
    geom_bar(stat="identity",position=position_dodge())+
    scale_fill_manual(values=c(col1,col2),name="Sex",breaks=c("female","male"),labels=c("Female", "Male"))+
    theme(legend.key=element_rect(color="black"))+
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymax=means+sems, ymin=means-sems),width=.2,position=position_dodge(.9))+
    ggtitle("Posttest Optimism score by Sex and Political Affiliation")+
    labs(x="Political Party Affiliation",y="Posttest Optimism Score\n(tens)")+
    scale_x_discrete(breaks=c("democrat","independent","republican"),labels=c("Democrat","Independent","Republican"))+
    theme(plot.title=element_text(size=15,face="bold",vjust=.5))+
    theme(axis.title.x=element_text(size=12,face="bold",vjust=-.25))+
    theme(axis.title.y=element_text(size=12,face="bold",vjust=1))+
    theme(axis.text.x=element_text(size=10,face="bold",color="black"))+
    theme(axis.text.y=element_text(size=10,face="bold",color="black"))+
    coord_cartesian(ylim=c(min(temp$means)-2*max(temp$sems),max(temp$means)+2*max(temp$sems)))+
    theme(panel.border=element_blank(),axis.line=element_line())+
    theme(panel.grid.major.x=element_blank())+
    theme(panel.grid.major.y=element_line(color="darkgrey"))+
    theme(panel.grid.minor.y=element_blank())+
    theme(legend.position=c(.8,.80))+
    theme(legend.background=element_blank())+
    theme(legend.background=element_rect(color="black"))+
    theme(legend.title=element_blank())+
    theme(legend.title=element_text(size=12))+
    theme(legend.title.align=.5)+
    theme(legend.text=element_text(size=10,face="bold"))
f

To see if optimism scores before and after watching AFHV vary depending on party affiliation, Im going to run a 2-way mixed ANOVA. Im using a mixed ANOVA because the same people indicated their optimism before and after the videos (i.e.a within-subjects factor) and because different people are affiliated with different political parties (i.e.a between-subjects factor).

summary(aov(optimismscore~testtime*sex+Error(subject/testtime),data=pols))
